VALUES
(43, 19, 16, 40, 27, 26, 31, NULL, 'Crucifixion of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the delivery of Jesus to be crucified. John 19:16 states that Jesus was led away to be crucified, while Matthew 27:26-31 describes the events leading up to that moment, including his scourging and mockery.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 16, 42, 23, 24, 25, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus'' Delivery to Crucifixion', 'Both passages emphasize the act of delivering Jesus to be crucified. In John, Jesus is led away for crucifixion, while in Luke, Pilate delivers Jesus to their will, indicating the fulfillment of the crucifixion process.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 16, 41, 15, 15, 20, 'delivered he him therefore unto them to be crucified', 'Connection of Jesus'' Crucifixion', 'Both passages emphasize the delivery of Jesus to be crucified. They describe the events leading to his crucifixion, highlighting the actions of Pilate and the soldiers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 17, 42, 23, 33, 33, 'place of a skull', 'Crucifixion Location Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the location of Jesus'' crucifixion, referred to as Golgotha in John and Calvary in Luke. This connection highlights the significance of the place where the events of the crucifixion occurred.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 17, 42, 14, 27, 27, 'bearing his cross', 'Bearing the Cross', 'Both passages emphasize the act of bearing one''s cross, linking the physical burden of Jesus in John to the spiritual commitment required of disciples in Luke. This connection highlights the significance of sacrifice in following Christ.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 17, 41, 15, 32, 32, 'bearing his cross', 'Connection of Crucifixion Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the act of crucifixion, with John mentioning Jesus bearing his cross and Mark depicting the mocking of Christ on the cross. This connection highlights the suffering and rejection faced by Jesus during his crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 17, 44, 7, 58, 58, NULL, 'Connection through Suffering and Death', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering and death in both passages. In John 19:17, Jesus bears his cross, symbolizing his impending crucifixion, while in Acts 7:58, Stephen is stoned, representing the persecution of early Christians.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 17, 58, 13, 11, 13, 'bearing his cross', 'Connection of Suffering and Reproach', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' suffering outside the city, paralleling the act of bearing the cross. Both passages emphasize the idea of bearing reproach in the context of sacrifice.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 17, 3, 16, 21, 22, 'bearing his cross', 'Connection of Bearing and Iniquities', 'Both passages emphasize the act of bearing burdens. In John 19:17, Jesus bears his cross, while in Leviticus 16:21, the goat bears the iniquities of the people.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 17, 3, 24, 14, 14, 'bearing his cross', 'Connection of Cursing and Bearing', 'This connection highlights the act of bearing a curse, as seen in John where Jesus bears his cross, and in Leviticus where the one who has cursed is brought forth. Both passages emphasize the communal aspect of judgment and punishment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 18, 23, 53, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection of Transgressors in Crucifixion', 'Both passages emphasize being ''numbered with the transgressors.'' John 19:18 describes Jesus'' crucifixion alongside two others, while Isaiah 53:12 explicitly states he was numbered with transgressors, highlighting the fulfillment of prophecy.', 'prophecy', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 18, 19, 22, 16, 16, NULL, 'Connection of Crucifixion Imagery', 'This connection highlights the act of piercing associated with Jesus'' crucifixion. Both passages emphasize the physical suffering endured during this event.', 'prophecy', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 18, 40, 27, 35, 38, 'two other with him', 'Crucifixion of Jesus and Thieves', 'Both passages emphasize the crucifixion of Jesus alongside two others. The mention of ''two other with him'' in John parallels the ''two thieves crucified with him'' in Matthew, highlighting the shared event.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 18, 40, 27, 44, 44, 'Jesus in the midst', 'Crucifixion of Jesus and Thieves', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of Jesus ''in the midst'' of two others during the crucifixion. Additionally, the mention of the thieves in Matthew highlights their role alongside Jesus, reinforcing the narrative of his crucifixion.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 18, 41, 15, 24, 27, 'two other with him', 'Crucifixion of Jesus and Thieves', 'Both passages emphasize the crucifixion of Jesus alongside two others, highlighting his central position. The mention of ''two thieves'' in Mark parallels the description of ''two other with him'' in John.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 18, 43, 18, 32, 32, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus'' Death', 'This connection highlights the fulfillment of Jesus'' prediction about his death. The mention of crucifixion in John 19:18 aligns with the prophecy in John 18:32 regarding the manner of his death.', 'prophecy', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 18, 48, 3, 13, 13, NULL, 'Crucifixion and the Curse', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' crucifixion as a fulfillment of the curse associated with hanging on a tree. Both passages emphasize the significance of Jesus'' position during crucifixion and its redemptive implications.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 19, 40, 27, 37, 37, 'THE KING OF THE JEWS', 'Accusation of Jesus'' Kingship', 'This connection highlights the shared theme of Jesus being identified as ''the King of the Jews'' in both passages. The wording in both verses emphasizes this title, linking them together in the context of His crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 19, 41, 15, 26, 26, 'THE KING OF THE JEWS', 'Connection of Accusation Titles', 'Both passages emphasize the title given to Jesus, identifying him as ''THE KING OF THE JEWS.'' This connection highlights the significance of this designation in the context of his crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 19, 42, 23, 38, 38, 'THE KING OF THE JEWS', 'Titles of Jesus on the Cross', 'Both passages emphasize the title given to Jesus, identifying him as ''THE KING OF THE JEWS.'' This connection highlights the significance of this proclamation in both accounts.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 19, 43, 19, 14, 14, NULL, 'Connection of Kingship in John', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' identity as ''King.'' In John 19:14, Pilate presents Jesus to the Jews as their King, while in John 19:19, the title on the cross explicitly identifies Him as ''THE KING OF THE JEWS.'' This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' kingship in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 19, 43, 1, 45, 46, 'JESUS OF NAZARETH', 'Connection of Jesus'' Identity', 'This connection highlights the identification of Jesus as ''Jesus of Nazareth'' in both passages. The first passage emphasizes His title as ''THE KING OF THE JEWS,'' while the second introduces Him as ''the son of Joseph'' from Nazareth, linking His origins to His royal claim.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 19, 44, 3, 6, 6, 'JESUS OF NAZARETH', 'Connection of Jesus of Nazareth', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' identity as ''Jesus of Nazareth.'' The first passage identifies Him as ''THE KING OF THE JEWS,'' while the second invokes His name for healing, linking His authority and identity.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 19, 44, 26, 9, 9, 'JESUS OF NAZARETH', 'Connection of Jesus of Nazareth', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of Jesus as ''Jesus of Nazareth.'' The first passage identifies Him as ''THE KING OF THE JEWS,'' while the second reflects on actions taken against His name, linking the two references to His significance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
