(43, 19, 20, 43, 19, 13, 13, NULL, 'Location and Language Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the geographical context of Jesus'' trial and crucifixion. The mention of ''Hebrew'' in both verses highlights the significance of language in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 20, 44, 21, 37, 37, NULL, 'Language and Identity in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the use of Greek, highlighting its significance in the context of communication and identity. In John 19:20, the inscription is presented in Greek, while in Acts 21:37, Paul is recognized for speaking Greek.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 20, 44, 22, 2, 2, 'in Hebrew', 'Language and Communication in Context', 'This connection highlights the use of Hebrew in both passages. In John 19:20, the title is written in Hebrew, while Acts 22:2 emphasizes speaking in the Hebrew tongue.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 20, 66, 16, 16, 16, NULL, 'Connection of Locations and Language', 'This connection highlights the significance of place and language in both passages. The mention of ''Hebrew'' in both John 19:20 and Revelation 16:16 emphasizes the cultural and linguistic context surrounding pivotal events in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 19, 20, 58, 13, 12, 12, NULL, 'Jesus'' Suffering Outside the Gate', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' crucifixion location and suffering. John 19:20 notes the proximity to the city, while Hebrews 13:12 highlights that Jesus suffered ''without the gate.'' This connection highlights the significance of Jesus'' sacrifice outside the city.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
